Rationale for Using Log Transformation on Grades in ‘reddit_jokes.json’

Despite the fact that the data does not follow an exponential distribution, a log transformation is applied to the grades. This decision is informed by several reasons:

Reducing Skewness

The distribution of grades is often right-skewed, with a concentration of values at the lower end and a long tail towards the higher end. A log transformation can help reduce this skewness, making the data more symmetric and, hence, more amenable to analysis techniques that assume normality.

Handling Outliers

Log transformation dampens the effect of outliers. Given that higher grades can vary widely and have a disproportionate effect on the mean, transforming the data reduces the impact of these extreme values.

Normalizing Variance

Variance in the data often increases with the value of the grades. The log transformation can help stabilize the variance across different ranges of scores, which is a desirable property for many statistical analyses.

Proportional Scaling

A log transformation ensures that changes in the transformed data represent proportional changes in the original data, which can be more intuitive for understanding differences between grades.

Diagnostic Plots for Goodness-of-Fit Assessment

The uploaded image displays a series of diagnostic plots commonly employed to evaluate the goodness-of-fit between a statistical distribution and a set of data points. Specifically, these plots compare empirical data (data points) to a theoretical exponential distribution. Each plot serves a distinct purpose:

Empirical and Theoretical Density Plot

This plot juxtaposes the empirical density (density of observed data) with the theoretical density of the exponential distribution. Black bars represent empirical density, while the red line illustrates the theoretical density. A close alignment suggests a good fit.

Q-Q (Quantile-Quantile) Plot

Used to compare quantiles of empirical data distribution with those of the theoretical distribution (exponential in this case). Points aligning with the reference line indicate agreement with the theoretical distribution. The image shows significant deviation, especially for higher quantiles, suggesting a potential mismatch with an exponential distribution.

Empirical and Theoretical CDFs (Cumulative Distribution Functions)

This plot compares the empirical cumulative distribution function (CDF) with the theoretical CDF of the exponential distribution. A close fit in the lower range is observed, but potential deviations arise as values increase.

P-P (Probability-Probability) Plot

Similar to the Q-Q plot, this plot compares cumulative probabilities. If the empirical data distribution matches the theoretical distribution, points should lie on the diagonal line. Most data points in the plot are near the diagonal, indicating a reasonable fit for most of the data range, with some deviations.

Overall Assessment: These plots collectively suggest that the exponential distribution may not be the best fit for the data, particularly at higher quantiles (as indicated by the Q-Q plot) and possibly in the tail of the CDF plot. The P-P plot suggests a reasonable fit for the lower to mid-range of the data. It’s essential to consider the goodness-of-fit test (gof) results, not visible in the image, for a more comprehensive statistical assessment.

Conclusion for first hypothesis:

After all test. We can reject \(H_0\). So our scores doesn’t have exponential distribution.

Testing the quality depends on category?

But before doing this calculation, we will exclude category “Miscellaneous”.

ANOVA Test

We used the Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) test because it allows us to determine if there are significant differences in joke ratings among multiple categories. ANOVA assesses whether the variation in ratings is due to the categories themselves rather than random chance. This is relevant to test whether the quality of jokes depends on their category, which is the focus of your hypotheses.

filtered_data <- stuff_data %>%
  filter(category != "Miscellaneous")

jokes_data <- filtered_data %>% select(rating, category)
result <- aov(rating ~ category, data = jokes_data)
summary(result)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
## category      41    101   2.470   1.797 0.00149 **
## Residuals   2416   3322   1.375                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Conclusion to third hypothesis

The ANOVA results reveal that the “category” factor has a statistically significant effect on joke ratings (F(41, 2416) = 1.797, p = 0.00149, **). This small p-value (p < 0.05) indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis.

Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis (H0) and conclude that the quality (rating) of a joke indeed depends on its category. In other words, there are significant differences in joke ratings among the categories. The variation in ratings is not solely due to random chance but is influenced by the category of the joke.

Final task which we want to done in our research is a model which will decide whether the joke is funny or not funny. For that purpose we decided to create naive bayes classifier.

First of all we need to clear our data. We will train our model using reddit_jokes.json and make prediction on stupidstuff.json and will calculate the accuracy of our model (we will prepare a test file in parallel).

First - data cleaning

reddit_jokes <- fromJSON('reddit_jokes.json')
stp_jokes <- fromJSON('stupidstuff.json')
stop_words <- data.frame(word = tolower(readLines("stop_words_mod.txt")))
colnames(stop_words)[colnames(stop_words) == "rating"] <- "score"
splitted_stop_words <- c(stop_words, "s")

# remove id column
reddit_jokes <- reddit_jokes[, -which(names(reddit_jokes) == "id")]
stp_jokes <- stp_jokes[, -which(names(stp_jokes) == "id")]
stp_jokes <- stp_jokes[, -which(names(stp_jokes) == "category")]

#merge title and body columns
reddit_jokes$body <- paste(reddit_jokes$title, reddit_jokes$body)

#remove title column
reddit_jokes <- reddit_jokes[, -which(names(reddit_jokes) == "title")]

#remove useless symols
reddit_jokes$body <- gsub("\\?|\\,|\\.|!|“|\"|”|…|:", "", reddit_jokes$body)
reddit_jokes$body <- gsub("\n\n|\n| - ", " ", reddit_jokes$body)
stp_jokes$body <- gsub("\\?|\\,|\\.|!|“|\"|”|…|:|'", "", stp_jokes$body)
stp_jokes$body <- gsub("\n\n|\n| - |  ", " ", stp_jokes$body)

#change all characters to lower case
reddit_jokes$body <- tolower(reddit_jokes$body)
stp_jokes$body <- tolower(stp_jokes$body)

stop_words_pattern <- paste0("\\b", paste(stop_words, collapse = "\\b|\\b"), "\\b")

# Filter out stop words and words with length smaller than 3
reddit_jokes <- reddit_jokes %>%
  mutate(body_filtered = str_replace_all(body, stop_words_pattern, "")) %>%
  mutate(body_filtered = str_replace_all(body_filtered, "\\b\\w{1,2}\\b", ""))

stp_jokes <- stp_jokes %>%
  mutate(body = str_replace_all(body, stop_words_pattern, "")) %>%
  mutate(body = str_replace_all(body, "\\b\\w{1,2}\\b", ""))

colnames(stp_jokes)[colnames(stp_jokes) == "rating"] <- "score"
stp_jokes <- stp_jokes[which(stp_jokes$body != ""), ]

Now our dataset only contains jokes without punctuation where there are only words longer than 3 characters. Also, words from stop_words_mod.txt (the file that contains the most common words) are missing.

But to make classifier we need to divide our jokes in two or more types. We will divide in types: funny and goofy. Class “funny” will contain jokes which has score higher than 2.5 and “goofy” which lower or equal to 2.5. May be this approach was good if we have the symetric distribution, but in our case data has very big skewness:

skewness(reddit_jokes$score)
## [1] 17.75724

So we need to divide our data set in two approximately equal parts. We decided to take such intervals: from 0 to 0.5 is “bad joke” and from 0.5 to 5 is “good joke”. We can have such classes, because if we look at the general situation on reddit or on the Internet as a whole: we will notice that after a comment gains reactions (in our case, a rating) more than a certain critical value, its popularity grows faster (very similar to the network effect in the economy) . Therefore, we can divide our jokes into approximately the same number of groups to make our model more accurate in identifying the category, as this effect extends to jokes as well.

However, there is a problem: our jokes has rating

cat("from", min(reddit_jokes$score),"to", max(reddit_jokes$score))
## from 0 to 48526

so we need to scale them (what we have done in previous sections). We will use logarithmic scaling

reddit_jokes$score <- log(reddit_jokes$score + 1)
reddit_jokes$score <- scales::rescale(reddit_jokes$score, to = c(0, 5))

Now lets divide jokes to categories

reddit_jokes$score <- ifelse(reddit_jokes$score > 0.5, "funny", "goofy")
stp_jokes$score <- ifelse(stp_jokes$score > 0.5, "funny", "goofy")

Now we have exactly the same groups

cat("Funny:", table(reddit_jokes$score[reddit_jokes$score == "funny"]), "\n")

cat("Not funny:", table(reddit_jokes$score[reddit_jokes$score == "goofy"]))

So now we can start to create a model:

Firstly make some neccessary preparation before set-uping model

reddit_jokes <- data.frame(reddit_jokes)
reddit_jokes <- subset(reddit_jokes, select = -body_filtered)
splitted_jokes <- unnest_tokens(reddit_jokes, "splitted", "body", token = "words")
split_data <- split(splitted_jokes, splitted_jokes$score)
container <- data.frame(splitted = character(0), types = character(0))

for (score in names(split_data)) {
  group <- data.frame(splitted = split_data[[score]], types = score)
  container <- bind_rows(container, group)
}
funny_df <- data.frame(splitted = split_data[["funny"]])
goofy_df <- data.frame(splitted = split_data[["goofy"]])

funny_count <- funny_df %>% count(split_data[["funny"]], sort = TRUE)
goofy_count <- goofy_df %>% count(split_data[["goofy"]], sort = TRUE)
tidy_t <- unnest_tokens(stp_jokes, "splitted", "score", token = "words")
naiveBayes <- setRefClass("naiveBayes",
                          
       fields = list(
         fit_model = "data.frame",
         word_count = "data.frame"
       ),
       methods = list(
                    fit = function(X, y)
                    {
                      tidy_t <- unnest_tokens(X, "splitted", "score", token = "words")
                      tidy_text <- tidy_t %>% filter(!splitted %in% splitted_stop_words)

                      .self$word_count <- tidy_text %>% count(splitted, sort = TRUE)
                     
                      df_for_words <- data.frame(matrix(0, nrow = nrow(.self$word_count['splitted']), ncol = length(y)))
                      
                      colnames(df_for_words) <- y
                      rownames(df_for_words) <- word_count$splitted

                      for(i in 1:nrow(df_for_words)) {
                        if (rownames(df_for_words[i, ]) %in% funny_count$splitted) {
                          df_for_words[i, 1] = 1
                        }
                        if (rownames(df_for_words[i, ]) %in% goofy_count$splitted) {
                          df_for_words[i, 2] = 1                          
                        }
                      }
                      .self$fit_model <- df_for_words
                    },
                    
                    predict = function(message)
                    {
                      message_list <- list(strsplit(tolower(message), " ")[[1]])
                      df_message <- data.frame(matrix(0, nrow=length(message_list[[1]]), ncol = 2))
                      all_words <- sum(.self$word_count$n)+length(message_list[[1]])
                      all_funny_words = sum(funny_count$n)
                      all_goofy_words = sum(goofy_count$n)
                      
                      funny_prob = all_funny_words/all_words
                      goofy_prob = all_goofy_words/all_words
                      
                      colnames(df_message) <- c('funny', 'goofy')
                      rownames(df_message) <- message_list[[1]]                     
                         
                      for (i in 1:nrow(df_message)) {
                        if (rownames(df_message[i, ]) %in% rownames(.self$fit_model)) {
                          if (rownames(df_message[i, ]) %in% funny_count$splitted) {
                            df_message[i, 1] = (funny_count[which(funny_count$splitted == rownames(df_message[i, ])), 3] + 1)/(all_funny_words+all_words)
                          } else {
                            df_message[i, 1] = 1/(all_funny_words+all_words)
                          }
                          if (rownames(df_message[i, ]) %in% goofy_count$splitted) {
                            df_message[i, 2] = (goofy_count[which(goofy_count$splitted == rownames(df_message[i, ])), 3] + 1)/(all_goofy_words+all_words)
                          } else {
                            df_message[i, 2] = 1/(all_goofy_words+all_words)                            
                          }
                        } else {
                            df_message[i, 1] = 1/(all_goofy_words+all_words)     
                            df_message[i, 2] = 1/(all_goofy_words+all_words)     
                        } 
                      }
                      
                      new_row = list(funny_prob, goofy_prob)
                      df_message = rbind(df_message, new_row)
                      
                      prob_for_message <- apply(df_message, 2, prod)
                    
                      return(names(prob_for_message[which(prob_for_message == max(prob_for_message))]))
                    }

))

model = naiveBayes()
temp_column <- reddit_jokes$body
reddit_jokes$body <- reddit_jokes$score
reddit_jokes$score <- temp_column

colnames(reddit_jokes)[1] <- "score"
colnames(reddit_jokes)[2] <- "body"

model$fit(reddit_jokes, c("funny", "goofy"))

Conclusion

The analysis revealed that the distribution of jokes’ quality ratings does not follow an exponential distribution. This suggests that the ratings of jokes do not exhibit the typical characteristics of an exponential distribution, such as rapidly decreasing probabilities with increasing ratings.

The research also showed that the quality (rating) of jokes is not significantly influenced by their length. This implies that longer jokes do not necessarily receive higher ratings, and shorter jokes are not inherently rated lower. The length of a joke does not appear to be a strong predictor of its quality in this dataset.

A significant finding of the research is that the quality of jokes is dependent on their category. The category or topic of a joke plays a crucial role in determining its quality. The analysis, as supported by ANOVA, indicated that there are significant differences in joke ratings among different joke categories. This suggests that the variation in ratings is not solely due to random chance but is influenced by the category of the joke.

Also we created Bayesian model to evaluate whether a joke is funny or not. This model uses Bayesian methods to assess the likelihood of a joke being humorous based on various factors. While the model provides a quantitative approach to humor assessment.

It’s important to remember that the accuracy of joke analysis results is always limited by subjectivity and the differences in people’s tastes. So when interpreting joke data, it’s important to be cautious and understand that these are just ratings that reflect the tastes and preferences of a specific audience.

Analyzing joke data can provide general insights into trends and patterns, but it can’t always accurately predict which joke will appeal to each individual.
